         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">9/3/87 ¶ Dear Mr Moore, ¶  ¶ So soon, as I learned from your letter, ¶  that the Phylloxera-Commission there desires to appoint an Inspector, ¶  I wrote to Mr M'Alpine, who is the most eligible person...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.03.09</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Charles Moore</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML DOC.3061, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">9/3/87</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Mr Moore,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>So soon, as I learned from your letter,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> that the Phylloxera-Commission there desires to appoint an Inspector,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>On 9 March 1887 the Phylloxera Board of NSW advertised for an Inspector with 'a practical knowledge of phylloxera insect…' (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Sydney mornng herald</seg>, 9 March 1887, p. 16).</p>
               </note> I wrote to Mr M'Alpine, who is the most eligible person here, so far as I know them, for being entrusted with that office, he having made the microscopic study of the diseases of plants a speciality. He came here from Edinburgh, where he was a Lecturer in natural sciences, about two years ago, and holds appointments on Ormond-College<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>University of Melbourne.</p>
               </note> and on the School of Pharmacy; but probably he would prefer a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Gov.</hi>
               </seg> Appointment, with prospects of Advancement in the service.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When I hear of him, I will let you know. If his service for this particular kind of work can be obtained for N.S.W., it will be a great advantage to your colony.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>McAlpine remained in Victoria and in 1890 was appointed vegetable pathologist in the Department of Agriculture.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>To the list of plants of your colony is still to be added <name key="Aizoon%20zygophylloides">Aizoon zygophylloides</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I need not repeat, that I will be happy to afford you every aid in the elaboration of the Flora of N.S.W., even to the extent of revising the msc; — but I could not do justice to the work, unless it was framed on the arrangement of my Census;<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B83.03.04.</p>
               </note> if the sequence of the orders and genera and the limitation of the genera and species was to be according to the Flora Australiensis,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and the law of priority is not to prevail in corrected nomenclature, your book would be quite "behind the times"; and I see endless difficulties, to reconcile the two arrangements. As a mere example I would briefly say, as I have no leisure to quote numerous cases, that even at <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Kew</hi>
               </seg> such genera as <name key="Polanisia">Polanisia</name> are given up. A careful monographer on the Continent working out the <name key="Tiliaceae">Tiliaceae</name>, abolished also <name key="Echinocarpus">Echinocarpus</name>, merging it, as first done by me, into <name key="Sloanea">Sloanea</name>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Schumann (1886), p 170; B83.03.04, p. 17.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The description of <name key="Euroschinus%20falcatus">Euroschinus falcatus</name> in the Flora<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1, pp. 490-1.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> is partly composed of that plant and partly of <name key="Ganophyllum%20falcatum">Ganophyllum falcatum</name>, a plant of a different order even. Look on the plates of <name key="Eremophila">Eremophila</name>s and <name key="Pholidia">Pholidia</name>s in my Atlas, and you will see the impossibility of keeping them generically apart.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See B86.08.05. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4, assigned to </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Pholidia">Pholidia</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">a number of forms that M had described as species of </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eremophila">Eremophila</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">, but in </seg>B83.03.04<seg style="">, M restored them to </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eremophila">Eremophila</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> These and hundreds of other things corrected by my Fragmenta and my Census, have been recognized as correct by Prof Tate, a man of great research, in his dealing with S.A plants; and I should feel much humbled, if my superior experiences in Australia, a land never visited by Bentham, were set aside in any local Floras here. But it is not my private feeling on the subject, which <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>prompts me, to urge on you the adoption of the Census, but my persuasion that my views are the correct ones after 40 years of study in Australia. Moreover the Flora could not be largely used and followed without permission of the publisher, who would likely object to the transcribing as undue competition.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In C. Moore (1893), ‘the systematic arrangement adopted … is that of Baron von Mueller in his “Census of Australian Plants”’ (p. xiv). The accompanying dichotomous keys to the genera and species follow ‘the same form as that invented by Dr. J. Neger in his “Flora of Germany”, published in N</seg>ü<seg style="">rnberg in 1871’ (p. xii). </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> have true petals, but the calyx reduced as in many spec. of <name key="Rhododendron">Rhododendron</name> [...] <name key="Eriostemon">Eriostemon</name> &amp;c. Even <name key="Loranthaceae">Loranthaceae</name> B. &amp; H. had lately among monochlamydeae!</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
